/status/1252624119335706625|title=The Department of Health confirms that today a further nine people have sadly lost their lives to Covid-19. Figures today in the recently launched dashboard reported an incorrect figure. The report has been temporarily suspended.|date=21 April 2020|via=Department of Health}}</ref>\n|-\n|22 Apr 2020 || 146 || 9 || 701 || 229 || <ref>{{cite web|url=https://twitter.com/healthdpt/status/1252999868852973568|title=UPDATE on coronavirus (#COVID19) in NI.|date=22 April 2020|via=Department of Health}}</ref>\n|-\n|23 Apr 2020 || 142 || 13 || 858 || 181 || <ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.health-ni.gov.uk/news/daily-covid-19-figures-23-april-2020|title=Daily Covid-19 figures - 23 April 2020|date=23 April 2020|via=Department of Health}}</ref>\n|-\n|24 Apr 2020 || 106 || 15 || 636 || 60 || <ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.health-ni.gov.uk/news/daily-covid-19-figures-24-april-2020|title=Daily Covid-19 figures - 24 April 2020|date=24 April 2020|via=Department of Health}}</ref>\n|-\n|25 Apr 2020 || 104 || 16 || 794 || 38 || <ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.health-ni.gov.uk/news/daily-covid-19-figures-25-april-2020|title=Daily Covid-19 figures - 25 April 2020|date=25 April 2020|via=Department of Health}}</ref>\n|-\n|26 Apr 2020 || 82 || 5 || 686 ||  || <ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.health-ni.gov.uk/news/daily-covid-19-figures-26-april-2020|title=Daily Covid-19 figures - 26 April 2020|date=26 April 2020|via=Department of Health}}</ref>\n|-\n|27 Apr 2020 || 66 || 10 || 597 ||  || <ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.health-ni.gov.uk/news/daily-covid-19-figures-27-april-2020|title=Daily Covid-19 figures - 27 April 2020|date=27 April 2020|via=Department of Health}}</ref>\n|-\n|28 Apr 2020 || 34 || 20 || 807 || 340 || <ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.health-ni.gov.uk/news/daily-covid-19-figures-28-april-2020|title=Daily Covid-19 figures - 28 April 2020|date=28 April 2020|via=Department of Health}}</ref>\n|-\n|29 Apr 2020 || 55 || 9 || 1447 || 143 || <ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.health-ni.gov.uk/news/daily-covid-19-figures-29-april-2020|title=Daily Covid-19 figures - 29 April 2020|date=29 April 2020|via=Department of Health}}</ref>\n|-\n|30 Apr 2020 || 73 || 9 || 2243 || 164 || <ref name=\"30 April\"/>\n|-\n|1 May 2020 || 87 || 18 || 1319 || || <ref name=\"1 May\"/>\n|-\n|2 May 2020 || 63 || 11 || 1328 || 260 || <ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.bbc.co.uk/news/live/uk-northern-ireland-52435090|title=Coronavirus in NI on 2 May|date=2 May 2020|via=BBC}}</ref>\n|-\n|3 May 2020 || 78 || 5 || 1204 || 59 || <ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.bbc.co.uk/news/live/uk-northern-ireland-52435093|title=Coronavirus in NI on 3 May\n|date=3 May 2020|via=BBC}}</ref>\n|-\n! Total || 3,767 || 381 || 29,629* || 3,829* ||\n|}\n\n*Total amount of tests will not add up to the total of daily tests listed above as test numbers are not always announced on a daily basis, however when they are a new overall total is announced as well.\n*Some data is taken from the Department of Health COVID-19 dashboard which updates daily. \n*The data for recovered cases is taken from daily updates from the Department of Health regarding hospital discharges. This data is a combination of suspected and confirmed COVID-19 cases in hospitals so it may be a larger figure than confirmed cases.\n\n==See also==\n* [[COVID-19 pandemic in the United Kingdom]]\n** [[COVID-19 pandemic in England]]\n** [[COVID-19 pandemic in Scotland]]\n** [[COVID-19 pandemic in Wales]]\n** [[COVID-19 pandemic in London]]\n* [[COVID-19 pandemic in the Republic of Ireland]]\n* [[Caroline McElnay]], the [[County Antrim]] native directing [[COVID-19 pandemic in New Zealand|New Zealand]]'s battle against the virus\n\n==References==\n{{Reflist}}\nhttps://files.nisra.gov.uk/Births,%20Deaths%20and%20Marriages/Weekly-Deaths-Dashboard.html\n\n==Further reading==\n* {{cite news|url=https://www.irishtimes.com/news/ireland/irish-news/meet-the-irish-woman-near-the-top-of-new-zealand-s-covid-19-response-1.4224223|title=Meet the Irish woman near the top of New Zealand's Covid-19 response: Our advantage is that we are an island nation' \u2013 Dr Caroline McElnay|first=Mike|last=Milotte|date=9 April 2020|work=[[The Irish Times]]|location=[[Auckland]]}}\n\n==External links==\n* [https://www.nhs.uk/conditions/coronavirus-covid-19/ Coronavirus (COVID-19) on the NHS website]\n* [https://www.gov.uk/government/topical-events/coronavirus-covid-19-uk-government-response Coronavirus (COVID-19): UK government response]\n* [https://www.legislation.gov.uk/uksi/2020/129/contents/made The Health Protection (Coronavirus) Regulations 2020]. Legislation.gov.uk\n* [https://www.publichealth.hscni.net/publications/advice-covid-19-coronavirus Public Health Agency] \u2013 Advice on COVID-19 (coronavirus)\n* [https://www.worldometers.info/coronavirus/country/uk/ Worldometer UK Statistics] \u2013 Worldometer graphs and statistics for the UK\n\n{{2019\u201320 coronavirus pandemic}}\n{{Coronavirus pandemic in the United Kingdom|state=expanded}}\n{{Portal bar|United Kingdom|Medicine|Viruses}}\n\n[[Category:2020 coronavirus pandemic in Northern Ireland| ]]\n[[Category:2020 coronavirus pandemic in Ireland|Northern Ireland]]\n[[Category:2020 coronavirus pandemic in the United Kingdom|Northern Ireland]]\n[[Category:2020 in Northern Ireland]]\n[[Category:Medical outbreaks in Northern Ireland]]\n", "text_old": "{{About|the coronavirus pandemic in Northern Ireland|the pandemic in Republic of Ireland|COVID-19 pandemic in the Republic of Ireland}}\n{{short description|Ongoing COVID-19 viral pandemic in Northern Ireland}}\n{{Use dmy dates|date=April 2020}}\n{{Use British English|date=April 2020}}\n{{Infobox pandemic\n| name            = 2020 coronavirus pandemic in Northern Ireland\n| map1            = \n| legend1         = \n| map2            = \n| legend2         = \n| map3            = \n| legend3         = \n| disease         = [[Coronavirus disease 2019]] (COVID-19)\n| virus_strain    = [[Severe acute respiratory syndrome coronavirus 2|Severe acute respiratory syndrome<br/>coronavirus 2]] (SARS-CoV-2)\n| source          = [[Bat]]s or, possibly, [[pangolin]]s<ref>{{cite journal|url=https://www.nature.com/articles/s41586-020-2169-0_reference.pdf|title=Identifying SARS-CoV-2 related coronaviruses in Malayan pangolins|journal=[[Nature (journal)|Nature]]|date=26 March 2020|accessdate=26 March 2020|doi=10.1038/s41586-020-2169-0|first1=Tommy Tsan-Yuk|last1=Lam|first2=Marcus Ho-Hin|last2=Shum|first3=Hua-Chen|last3=Zhu|first4=Yi-Gang|last4=Tong|first5=Xue-Bing|last5=Ni|first6=Yun-Shi|last6=Liao|first7=Wei|last7=Wei|first8=William Yiu-Man|last8=Cheung|first9=Wen-Juan|last9=Li|first10=Lian-Feng|last10=Li|first11=Gabriel M.|last11=Leung|first12=Edward C.|last12=Holmes|first13=Yan-Ling|last13=Hu|first14=Yi|last14=Guan|pmid=32218527}}</ref><ref name=\"WHO report 28 February 2020\">{{cite web|url=https://www.who.int/docs/default-source/coronaviruse/who-china-joint-mission-on-covid-19-final-report.pdf|title=Report of the WHO-China Joint Mission on Coronavirus Disease 2019 (COVID-19)|date=16\u201324 February 2020|accessdate=8 March 2020|author=WHO\u2013China Joint Mission|work=[[World Health Organization]]}}</ref><ref name=\"ia56U\">{{cite journal|title=Mystery deepens over animal source of coronavirus|journal=[[Nature (journal)|Nature]]|volume=579|pages=18\u201319|date=26 February 2020|doi=10.1038/d41586-020-00548-w|pmid=32127703|vauthors=Cyranoski D|issue=7797|bibcode=2020Natur.579...18C|doi-access=free}}</ref>\n| location        = [[Northern Ireland]]\n| first_case      = [[Belfast]]\n| arrival date    = 29 February 2020 <br />({{Age in years, months, weeks and days|month1=03|day1=01|year1=2020|month2=|day2=|year2=}})\n| origin          = [[China]]\n| confirmed_cases = 3,836 <small>(as of 4 May 2020)</small><ref name=\"cis\">{{cite web |title=Coronavirus in Northern Ireland|url=https://www.health-ni.gov.uk/news/ |website=Department of Health|accessdate=20 March 2020}}</ref> <!--PLEASE KEEP UPDATED-->\n| deaths          = 387 <small>(as of 4 May 2020)</small><ref name=\"cis\"/> <!--PLEASE KEEP UPDATED HERE & IN LEAD-->\n| website         = [https://www.health-ni.gov.uk/ Department of Health Northern Ireland]\n}}\n\nThe [[2019\u201320 coronavirus pandemic|ongoing coronavirus pandemic]] reached [[Northern Ireland]] on 29 February 2020. According to the [[Department of Health (Northern Ireland)|Department of Health]], 387 <!--PLEASE KEEP UPDATED--> people have died after testing positive for coronavirus,<ref name=\"cis\"/> both in hospitals and care homes (see [[#Statistics|Statistics]]). Northern Ireland has the lowest recorded coronavirus death rate [[COVID-19 pandemic in the United Kingdom|in the United Kingdom]] and a lower rate than the [[Republic of Ireland]].<ref name=\"death rate\">[https://www.newsletter.co.uk/news/politics/coronavirus-pro-rata-ni-has-fewer-deaths-roi-or-gb-big-caveats-2535202 \"Coronavirus: Pro rata, NI has fewer deaths than RoI or GB\"]. ''[[The News Letter]]'', 9 April 2020.</ref> It is also carrying out more [[COVID-19 testing|tests]] ''per capita'' than the other [[countries of the United Kingdom]].<ref name=\"test rate\">[https://www.bbc.co.uk/news/52149297 \"Coronavirus: How England lags behind other UK nations on testing\"]. [[BBC News]], 9 April 2020.</ref>\n\nAs in the rest of the UK, all \"non-essential\" travel and contact with people outside one's home is restricted for the whole population, and almost all businesses, venues, facilities and places of worship are shut. Major events such as [[Saint Patrick's Day]] and [[The Twelfth]] were cancelled. A lengthy lockdown is forecast to severely damage the economy and lead to a large rise in unemployment.\n\nThe [[Health and Social Care in Northern Ireland|health service]] worked to raise hospital capacity. In mid-April, modelling by the Department of Health indicated that the health service in Northern Ireland could cope with the expected peak in cases.<ref name=\"newsletter.co.uk\">[https://www.newsletter.co.uk/news/politics/coronavirus-ni-now-peak-pandemic-it-may-be-less-devastating-feared-says-robin-swann-2539751 \"Coronavirus: NI now in peak of pandemic \u2013 but it may be less devastating than feared, says Robin Swann\"]. ''The Newsletter'', 15 April 2020. Quote: \"If our modelling is accurate, this should be more than sufficient capacity to meet this surge. In the event of an extreme surge, Northern Ireland\u2019s first Nightingale Hospital has now been established at Belfast City Hospital\".</ref> On 21 April, Northern Ireland's chief scientific advisor said the [[Flatten the curve|curve of new cases had flattened]], and evidence suggests Northern Ireland had passed the peak of its outbreak.<ref name=\"curve flattens\">[https://www.bbc.co.uk/news/uk-northern-ireland-52375614 \"Coronavirus: NI outlook positive as curve 'flattens'\"]. BBC News, 21 April 2020. Quotes: \"The curve for cases of Covid-19 in Northern Ireland is flattening and we could soon be on the downward slope, Northern Ireland's chief scientific advisor has said \u2026 Recent reductions in the daily number of hospital admissions as well as the number of deaths suggest that Northern Ireland passed the peak of its outbreak several days ago.\"</ref>\n\n==Timeline==\n{{align|right|{{2019\u201320 coronavirus pandemic data/Northern Ireland medical cases chart}}}}\n\n===February 2020===\n\nThe [[Health and Social Care in Northern Ireland|HSC]] began testing for COVID-19 during February 2020, as of 19 February there were 35 completed tests all of which returned negative results.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.publichealth.hscni.net/sites/default/files/2020-02/COVID-19%20-%2020%20February%202020.pdf |title=Novel coronavirus (2019-nCoV) |accessdate=20 February 2020|work=[[Health and Social Care in Northern Ireland]]}}</ref> On 27 February, the [[Health and Social Care (Northern Ireland)|HSC]] confirmed that the first presumptive case had been discovered in Northern Ireland in a woman who had returned from [[Italy]], the case was sent to the [[Public Health England]] reference laboratory where it was confirmed as Northern Ireland's first case on 29 February.<ref name=\"Belfast Telegraph\">{{cite news|url=https://www.belfasttelegraph.co.uk/news/health/coronavirus/first-northern-ireland-coronavirus-case-confirmed-as-drive-through-test-centre-set-up-at-antrim-hospital-39001866.html |title=First Northern Ireland coronavirus case confirmed as 'drive-through' test centre set up at Antrim hospital |accessdate=29 February 2020|work=[[Belfast Telegraph]]}}</ref><ref name=\"Belfast Telegraph\"/>\n\n===March 2020===\n\nCases continued to rise throughout early March with cases rising to seven by the end of the first week.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.publichealth.hscni.net/sites/default/files/2020-03/COVID-19%20-%207%20March%202020.pdf |title=SITUATION UPDATE 7 March 2020 Novel coronavirus (2019-nCoV) |accessdate=7 March 2020| work=[[Health and Social Care in Northern Ireland]]}}</ref> On 9 March [[Belfast City Council]] voted to cancel the annual [[St Patricks Day|St Patrick's Day]] parade in the city.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.bbc.com/news/world-europe-51806551By |title=Coronavirus: Irish St Patrick's Day parades cancelled |accessdate=9 March 2020|work=[[BBC]]}}</ref> By the end of the second week the HSC started to advise people showing symptoms to isolate for seven days, cases had also jumped to 45 by the 15th March.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.publichealth.hscni.net/sites/default/files/2020-03/COVID%2019%20%E2%80%93%2015%20March%202020.pdf |title=Guidance for people with confirmed or possible coronavirus |accessdate=15 March 2020|work=[[Health and Social Care in Northern Ireland]]}}</ref> On St Patrick's Day, parades across all of Northern Ireland had been cancelled as cases reached 52.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.bbc.com/news/live/uk-northern-ireland-51923744 |title=Coronavirus in NI on 17 March: Tuesday updates |accessdate=17 March 2020|work=[[BBC]]}}</ref>\n\nOn 19 March, Northern Ireland recorded its first death from COVID-19, with cases reaching 77.<ref name=\"19 Mar\">{{cite news|url=https://www.bbc.com/news/uk-northern-ireland-51958241 |title=Coronavirus: First death confirmed in NI |accessdate=19 March 2020|work=[[BBC]]|date=19 March 2020 }}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.rte.ie/news/2020/0319/1124116-first-covid-19-death-in-northern-ireland-announced/ |title=First Covid-19 death in Northern Ireland announced as testing increased |accessdate=19 March 2020|work=[[RTE]]|date=19 March 2020 }}</ref> Reacting to the news, [[First Minister and deputy First Minister of Northern Ireland|First Minister]] [[Arlene Foster]] said \"This is a sad day for Northern Ireland. Our thoughts and prayers are first and foremost with the family and friends of the patient who has died. And we are immeasurably grateful to our health service staff who cared for this person. This is not unexpected news. We knew that this pandemic would inevitably cost precious lives. We cannot stop it. But it is incumbent on all of us to do whatever we can to slow its spread and shield those most vulnerable from the effects of this virus.\"<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.rte.ie/news/2020/0319/1124116-first-covid-19-death-in-northern-ireland-announced/ |title=First Covid-19 death in Northern Ireland announced as testing increased |accessdate=19 March 2020|work=[[RTE]]|date=19 March 2020 }}</ref> On 22 March, a second person died from the coronavirus, with cases rising to 128.<ref name=\"22 Mar\"/>\n\nOn 20 March, the [[UK Government]] announced measures to further tackle the spread of the virus which included closing bars, restaurants, gyms and many other social venues.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.bbc.com/news/uk-51981653 |title=UK pubs and restaurants told to shut in virus fight|accessdate=20 March 2020|work=[[BBC]]}}</ref> The government also announced measures to help struggling businesses including covering up to 80% of wages lost due to the pandemic.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.bbc.com/news/business-51982005 |title=Coronavirus: Government to pay up to 80% of workers' wages |accessdate=20 March 2020|work=[[BBC]]}}</ref> Cases confirmed by 20 March were 86 in total.<ref name=\"20 Mar\">{{cite web|url=https://www.bbc.com/news/live/uk-northern-ireland-51972282 |title=As it happened: Coronavirus in NI on March 20 |accessdate=20 March 2020|work=[[BBC]]}}</ref> On 21 March, Northern Ireland suffered its largest increase in new cases to date with 22 new cases confirmed.<ref name=\"21 Mar\">{{cite web|url=https://www.itv.com/news/utv/2020-03-21/twenty-two-new-coronavirus-cases-in-northern-ireland/ |title=Twenty-two new coronavirus cases in Northern Ireland|accessdate=21 March 2020|work=[[ITV (TV network)|ITV]]}}</ref> On 22 March, a second person died from the virus.<ref name=\"22 Mar\">{{cite news|url=https://www.bbc.com/news/uk-northern-ireland-51994429 |title=Coronavirus: Second coronavirus-related death confirmed|accessdate=22 March 2020|work=[[BBC]]|date=22 March 2020}}</ref>\n\nOn 23 March, the government announced that new measures were to be introduced to increase social distancing, with wide-ranging restrictions made on freedom of movement, enforceable in law,<ref name=PM-address-2020-03-23>{{Cite news|url=https://www.bbc.com/news/uk-52012432|title=PM announces strict new curbs on life in UK|date=2020-03-23|work=BBC News|access-date=2020-03-23|language=en-GB}}</ref> for a planned \"lockdown\" period intended to last for three weeks.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.itv.com/news/2020-03-23/boris-johnson-downing-street-coronavirus-update/|title=Boris Johnson orders three-week lockdown of UK to tackle coronavirus spread|website=ITV News|language=en|access-date=2020-03-23}}</ref>\n\nThe government directed people to stay at home throughout this period, with the only following exceptions:<ref name=\":1\">{{Cite news|url=https://www.theguardian.com/uk-news/2020/mar/23/boris-johnsons-address-to-the-nation-in-full|title=Boris Johnson's address to the nation in full|date=2020-03-23|work=The Guardian|access-date=2020-03-23|language=en-GB|issn=0261-3077|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20200323204915/https://www.theguardian.com/uk-news/2020/mar/23/boris-johnsons-address-to-the-nation-in-full|archive-date=23 March 2020|url-status=live}}</ref>\n* essential purchases\n* once-daily exercise, either alone or with members of their household\n* medical needs\n*providing care for others\n* essential work travel where working from home is not possible\n\nMany other non-essential activities, including all public gatherings and social events except funerals, are to be proscribed.<ref name=PM-address-2020-03-23/>\n\nA third victim died from COVID-19 on 23 March, followed by two more deaths on 24 March.<ref>{{cite news|url=https://www.bbc.co.uk/news/uk-northern-ireland-52019102 |title=Coronavirus: 'I didn't get to kiss my mum goodbye'|accessdate=24 March 2020|work=[[BBC]]|date=24 March 2020}}</ref><ref name=\"24 Mar\">{{cite news|url=https://www.bbc.co.uk/news/uk-52012915 |title=Coronavirus restrictions 'will last more than three weeks'|accessdate=24 March 2020|work=[[BBC]]|date=24 March 2020\n}}</ref> On 25 March, the largest increase in new cases to date was recorded as cases rose by 37 to 209, with 2 new deaths also being confirmed.<ref name=\"25 Mar\">{{cite news|url=https://www.bbc.co.uk/news/uk-northern-ireland-52038992 |title=Coronavirus: Seven deaths confirmed in Northern Ireland|accessdate=25 March 2020|work=[[BBC]]|date=25 March 2020}}</ref> Speaking at a press conference on 25 March, Northern Ireland's Chief Medical Officer Dr Michael McBride said he believes the actual figure of cases to be \"many thousands\" and testing would increase to approximately 1000 new tests everyday.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.rte.ie/news/ulster/2020/0325/1126361-northern-ireland-coronavirus/ |title=Seventh death in NI, 'thousands' believed to have virus|accessdate=25 March 2020|work=[[RTE]]|date=25 March 2020|last1=Kearney|first1=Vincent}}</ref>\n\nOn 26 March, a further 3 people died from the virus with 32 new confirmed cases.<ref name=\"27 Mar\">{{cite news|url=https://www.bbc.co.uk/news/uk-northern-ireland-52051139 |title=Coronavirus: No hospital visits under NI Covid-19 surge plans|accessdate=26 March 2020|work=[[BBC]]|date=26 March 2020|last1=Smyth|first1=Catherine}}</ref> On 27 March, 34 new cases and 3 new deaths were confirmed, with leading GPs in Northern Ireland writing an open letter calling for a complete lockdown, stating \"Please hear and act on our heartfelt plea and move to adopt a 'complete lockdown' as we have seen in other countries, at the earliest opportunity. Time is of the essence.\".<ref name=\"27 Mar\"/> On 28 March, Northern Ireland experienced the highest rate of increased new cases yet with 49 new cases, and a further 2 deaths.<ref name=\"28 Mar\">{{cite news|url=https://www.bbc.com/news/uk-northern-ireland-52078043 |title=Coronavirus: Two more people die in Northern Ireland|accessdate=28 March 2020|work=[[BBC]]|date=28 March 2020}}</ref>\n\n[[File:Belfast COVID19 Traffic Management Sign.jpg|thumb|Electronic display sign normally used for traffic management displays COVID19-related advices on an almost deserted Chichester Street in Belfast City Centre, 24 March.]]\nOn the evening of the 28 March the [[Northern Ireland Executive]] announced new stricter measures to combat the spread of the virus. Measures included:{{citation needed|date=April 2020}}\n\n* The ability to force businesses to shut and crack down on people who leave their homes without a \"reasonable excuse\".\n* Penalties, ranging from fixed penalty notices to fines of up to \u00a35,000, are being introduced as enforcement.\n* Anyone who can work from home must work from home\n* Employers must facilitate working from home where it is feasible\n* No employer should compel an employee to come to work if it is feasible to work from home\n* Every employer must take all reasonable steps to safeguard the health, safety and wellbeing of employees during the COVID-19 emergency, whether working from home or in the workplace\n* Every employer must have particular regard to the safety of employees in the workplace and must put into effect the guidance on social distancing issued by the Department for the Economy\n* Every employer has a legal duty to ensure, so far as it is reasonably practicable, the health, safety and welfare at work of all employees\n* Where a business is failing to observe the Department for the Economy guidance and breaching the legal duty on health and safety, the statutory authorities will take robust action, which may include prosecution for criminal offences\n* Where necessary, the Executive Office will also use its power of direction to close or restrict businesses that do not ensure the safety of their employees.\n\nCommenting on the new measures, Arlene Foster said \"We are asking the people of Northern Ireland to make fundamental changes to how they live their lives. But we are doing this to keep you safe, to flatten the curve of the Covid-19 infection so that the health service has the capacity to deal with those who need their help the most.\" Deputy First Minister [[Michelle O'Neill]] also commented \"Each one of us has a personal responsibility to do everything we can to fight back against Covid-19 for the good of everyone across society. We will use every power we have to ensure people stay at home so that we save as many lives as we possibly can.\"<ref>{{cite news|url=https://www.bbc.com/news/uk-northern-ireland-52079959 |title=Coronavirus: New regulations come into force|accessdate=28 March 2020|work=[[BBC]]|date=28 March 2020}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.rte.ie/news/2020/0328/1127017-northern-irish-figures/ |title=Sweeping new powers to combat virus for Northern Ireland|accessdate=28 March 2020|work=[[RTE]]|date=28 March 2020|last1=Kearney|first1=Vincent}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.executiveoffice-ni.gov.uk/news/executive-approves-new-powers-protect-public |title=Executive approves new powers to protect the public|accessdate=28 March 2020|work=NI Executive|date=28 March 2020}}  [[File:UKOpenGovernmentLicence.svg|30px]] Text was copied from this source, which is available under a [http://www.nationalarchives.gov.uk/doc/open-government-licence/version/3/  Open Government Licence v3.0]. \u00a9 Crown copyright.</ref>\n\nOn 29 March, new cases announced by the [[Public Health Agency (Northern Ireland)|Public Health Agency]] were 86 and 6 new deaths, the highest for both in a single day to date.<ref name=\"29 Mar\">{{cite web|url=https://www.bbc.com/news/uk-northern-ireland-52084560 |title=Coronavirus: Six more deaths in Northern Ireland|accessdate=29 March 2020|work=[[BBC]]}}</ref>\n\nFollowing the announcement on 31 March that there were 53 new cases and 6 new deaths, the totals at the end of the month of March were 586 confirmed cases and 28 deaths.<ref name=\"31 Mar\">{{cite news|url=https://www.bbc.co.uk/news/uk-northern-ireland-52104195 |title=Coronavirus: Six more people die in Northern Ireland|accessdate=31 March 2020|work=[[BBC]]|date=31 March 2020}}</ref>\n\n===April 2020===\n\n[[File:A_deserted_A1_near_Newry.jpg|thumb|A deserted A1 on the outskirts of [[Newry]] during lockdown on 4 April.]]\nOn 1 April, a further 103 cases and 2 deaths were confirmed as Health Minister Robin Swann warned that 3000 people could die in the first wave of the pandemic.<ref name=\"1 April\">{{cite news|url=https://www.bbc.co.uk/news/uk-northern-ireland-52121143 |title=Coronavirus: NI could see 3,000 deaths in 'first wave'|accessdate=1 April 2020|work=[[BBC]]|date=April 2020}}</ref> On 2 April, 85 more cases and 6 more deaths were reported, bringing the total number of confirmed cases and deaths to 774 and 36 respectively.<ref name=\"2 April\">{{cite news|url=https://www.belfasttelegraph.co.uk/news/health/coronavirus/coronavirus-updates-diane-dodds-outlines-massive-shock-to-economy-as-six-further-deaths-in-northern-ireland-confirmed-39096431.html|title=Coronavirus updates: Diane Dodds outlines 'massive shock' to economy as six further deaths in Northern Ireland confirmed|work=[[Belfast Telegraph]]|first=Gareth|last=Cross|date=2 April 2020|accessdate=2 April 2020}}</ref> On 3 April, the largest increase in deaths and cases to date was published by the Public Health Agency with 130 cases and 12 deaths, bringing the total number of confirmed cases to 904 and the number of deaths to 48.<ref name=\"3 April\">{{cite news|url=https://www.belfasttelegraph.co.uk/news/health/coronavirus/coronavirus-updates-12-more-deaths-in-northern-ireland-and-130-new-covid-19-cases-39099564.html|title=Coronavirus updates: 12 more deaths in Northern Ireland and 130 new Covid-19 cases|work=[[Belfast Telegraph]]|first1=Andrew|last1=Madden|first2=Gareth|last2=Cross|date=3 April 2020|accessdate=3 April 2020}}</ref>\n\nOn 4 April, a further 94 new cases and 8 new deaths were announced, as Northern Ireland's first coronavirus testing centre for healthcare workers opened at the [[SSE Arena, Belfast]].<ref name=\"4 April\">{{cite news|url=https://www.bbc.com/news/uk-northern-ireland-52166720|title=Coronavirus: Eight more Covid-19 linked deaths in NI|work=[[BBC]]|date=4 April 2020|accessdate=4 April 2020}}</ref> Health Minister Robin Swann said the new testing facility in Belfast \u201cwill allay some of the concern and speculation we have had of late. I fully understand the frustration that we have not been able to scale up testing numbers more quickly. This is not down to a lack of will or action.There are significant challenges including laboratory and staffing capacity and the unprecedented levels of global demand for testing reagents and swabs.\u201d<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.bbc.com/news/uk-northern-ireland-5216037 |title=Coronavirus: First NHS testing centre to go live at SSE Arena|accessdate=4 April 2020|work=[[BBC]]}}</ref>\n\nIt was reported that more than 33,000 people so far had claimed unemployment benefits since the lockdown began, ten times the normal rate. Economists forecast that a lengthy lockdown and disruption would lead to hundreds of thousands of job losses.<ref>[https://www.bbc.co.uk/news/uk-northern-ireland-52161228 \"Coronavirus: Economic shock to NI becoming clear\"]. BBC News, 4 April 2020.</ref>\n\nOn 5 April, an additional 91 cases and 7 deaths were reported, bringing the total number of cases and deaths to 1,089 and 63 respectively.<ref name=\"5 April\">{{cite news|url=https://www.bbc.com/news/uk-northern-ireland-52174411|title=Coronavirus: Seven more Covid-19 linked deaths in NI|work=[[BBC]]|date=5 April 2020|accessdate=5 April 2020}}</ref>\n\nOn 6 April, the [[Orange Order]] announced that the annual [[The Twelve|12th July celebrations]] were cancelled, as a further 69 cases and 7 deaths were confirmed.<ref name=\"6 April\">{{cite news|url=https://www.bbc.co.uk/news/uk-northern-ireland-52184743|title=Coronavirus: Twelfth of July parades cancelled due to outbreak|work=[[BBC]]|date=6 April 2020|accessdate=6 April 2020}}</ref> A further 97 cases and 3 deaths were announced by the Public Health Agency on 7 April, as a second drive-through testing centre opened at an MOT centre in Belfast.<ref name=\"7 April\">{{cite news|url=https://www.bbc.co.uk/news/live/uk-northern-ireland-52158862|title=Coronavirus in NI on 7 April|work=[[BBC]]|date=7 April 2020|accessdate=7 April 2020}}</ref> With [[Easter]] weekend approaching, on 8 April, the [[Police Service of Northern Ireland]] warned people against visiting local beauty spots, as the death toll increased to 78 with 5 more deaths and 84 new cases being reported.<ref name=\"8 April\">{{cite news|url=https://www.belfasttelegraph.co.uk/news/health/coronavirus/coronavirus-updates-five-further-patients-die-after-contracting-covid-19-with-84-new-northern-ireland-cases-39112749.html|title=Coronavirus updates: Five further patients die after contracting Covid-19 with 84 new Northern Ireland cases|work=[[Belfast Telegraph]]|first=Mark|last=Edwards|date=8 April 2020|accessdate=8 April 2020}}</ref>\n\n[[File:Belfast_City_Hospital.jpg|thumb|upright=0.80|The tower at Belfast City Hospital has been converted to a field hospital.]]\nA further 4 deaths and 138 cases were confirmed on 9 April as experts predicted a deep [[Coronavirus recession|recession]] in Northern Ireland following the crisis.<ref name=\"9 April\">{{cite web|url=https://www.bbc.co.uk/news/uk-northern-ireland-52230030 |title=Coronavirus: NI economy facing a 'deep recession'|accessdate=9 April 2020|work=[[BBC]]}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.bbc.co.uk/news/uk-northern-ireland-52230806 |title=Coronavirus: Woman with Covid-19 'didn't want to die alone'|accessdate=9 April 2020|work=[[BBC]]}}</ref>  Research by the [[Northern Ireland Assembly]] Library found that Northern Ireland has a lower coronavirus death rate per capita than the other [[countries of the United Kingdom]], and a lower death rate than the Republic of Ireland.<ref name=\"death rate\"/> It was also revealed that Northern Ireland has a higher coronavirus testing rate per capita than the other countries of the United Kingdom.<ref name=\"test rate\"/>\n\nOn 10 April, a further 10 deaths and 112 cases were reported, bringing the totals to 92 deaths and 1,589 cases.<ref name=\"10 April\">{{cite web|url=https://www.belfasttelegraph.co.uk/news/health/coronavirus/coronavirus-updates-10-further-deaths-and-112-new-covid-19-northern-ireland-cases-confirmed-39118594.html |title=Coronavirus updates: 10 further deaths and 112 new Covid-19 Northern Ireland cases confirmed|accessdate=10 April 2020|work=[[BBC]]}}</ref>\n\nOn 11 April, 15 more deaths and 128 new cases were confirmed as Health Minister Robin Swann called on the [[British Army|Army]] for assistance in fighting the disease.<ref name=\"11 April\">{{cite web|url=https://www.bbc.co.uk/news/live/uk-northern-ireland-52158874 |title=As it happened: Coronavirus in NI on 11 April|accessdate=11 April 2020|work=[[BBC]]}}</ref> New cases increased by 89 to 1806, and deaths by 11 to 118 on 12 April.<ref name=\"12 April\">{{cite web|url=https://www.bbc.com/news/live/uk-northern-ireland-52158877 |title=As it happened: Coronavirus in NI on 12 April|accessdate=12 April 2020|work=[[BBC]]}}</ref> On 15 April, 6 more people died of the virus and another 121 cases were confirmed, as lock-down measures were extended for another three weeks with Deputy First Minister Michelle O'Neill warning against complacency stating, \"Our biggest danger in this period is complacency. The measures are showing positive results but if we relax our behaviour, we will be in danger.\" <ref name=\"15 April\">{{cite web|url=https://www.bbc.com/news/uk-northern-ireland-52298748 |title=Coronavirus: NI lockdown extended for three more weeks|accessdate=15 April 2020|work=[[BBC]]}}</ref>\n\nOn 15 April, [[Arlene Foster]], the [[First Minister of Northern Ireland]], extended the period of lockdown in Northern Ireland to 9 May, as 121 new cases and 6 new deaths were confirmed.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.bbc.com/news/uk-northern-ireland-52298748|title=Three-week extension to NI coronavirus lockdown|first=Jayne|last=McCormack|date=15 April 2020|via=www.bbc.co.uk}}</ref> Modelling by the [[Department of Health (Northern Ireland)|Department of Health]] indicated that Northern Ireland had reached the peak of its outbreak, and that the health service in Northern Ireland could now cope with the expected peak in cases. Swann said that the peak \"may now, potentially, be less severe than we had feared\".<ref name=\"newsletter.co.uk\"/>\n\nOn 20 April, the Department of Health launched a new website that provides daily statistic updates, such as information on hospital admissions and discharges, bed occupancy and a breakdown of case and death numbers by age and gender. Speaking about the launch, Health Minister Robin Swann said, \"It is vitally important to keep the public well informed. That includes the publication of statistics, as well as the all-important advice on how we keep ourselves and are loved ones safe.\" <ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.itv.com/news/utv/2020-04-19/new-covid-19-statistics-dashboard-launched-for-ni/|title=New Covid-19 statistics dashboard launched for NI|date=20 April 2020|via=ITV News}}</ref> The new website also confirmed that 2,307 COVID-19 patients had been discharged from hospital by 20 April.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.bbc.co.uk/news/uk-northern-ireland-52358440|title=Coronavirus: What do the new statistics tell us?|date=20 April 2020|via=BBC News}}</ref>\n\nOn 21 April, Northern Ireland's chief scientific advisor said the rising [[Flatten the curve|curve of new cases had flattened]] in Northern Ireland, and evidence suggests Northern Ireland had passed the peak of its outbreak. He said that the number of cases could fall to a low level by mid-May if social distancing rules are obeyed until then.<ref name=\"curve flattens\"/>\n\nOn 23 April, the First Minister, Arlene Foster, said Northern Ireland may be able to ease its lockdown sooner than other parts of the UK. She said that easing restrictions will depend when public health criteria are met, rather than on a timetable. The Health Minister said \"it's important we take our scientific guidance based on the science that is applicable to Northern Ireland\".<ref>[https://www.bbc.co.uk/news/uk-northern-ireland-52390373 \"Coronavirus: NI lockdown could lift at different pace, suggests Arlene Foster\"]. BBC News, 23 April 2020.</ref>\n\nAs the death toll increased to 338 on 29 April, Health Minister Robin Swann committed to maximum transparency with regards to statistics regarding the COVID-19 outbreak, stating \u201cI want to continue seeing the maximum possible transparency on this issue. I want to explore with NISRA if it is possible for it to report more frequently than once a week on deaths associated with Covid-19 across hospitals and the community. This is not straightforward and I want to thank all those who are working hard in this area to provide up to date and reliable statistics.\u201d <ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.health-ni.gov.uk/news/daily-covid-19-figures-29-april-2020|title=Daily Covid-19 figures - 29 April 2020|date=29 April 2020|via=Department of Health}}</ref>\n\nFollowing the announcement on 30 April that there were 73 new cases and 9 new deaths, the totals at the end of the month of April were 3536 confirmed cases and 347 deaths.<ref name=\"30 April\">{{cite web|url=https://www.health-ni.gov.uk/news/daily-covid-19-figures-30-april-2020|title=Daily Covid-19 figures - 30 April 2020|date=30 April 2020|via=Department of Health}}</ref>\n\nOn 30 April, the UK Statistics Authority wrote to the Permanent Secretary, Richard Pengelly stating there were gaps in the data and daily time series have been lost since the statistics began to be released through DoH news releases. It was further reported that daily surveillance statistics should be released in a transparent, easily accessible and orderly way.<ref>https://www.statisticsauthority.gov.uk/correspondence/letter-regarding-statistical-information-relating-to-covid-19-in-northern-ireland/</ref>\n\n===May 2020===\n\nOn 1 May, 18 more deaths from COVID-19 were announced, however, just 4 were from the previous 24 hours. NISRA recorded 393 deaths from COVID-19 by 24 April compared to 299 deaths recorded by Department of Health.<ref name=\"1 May\">{{cite web|url=https://www.bbc.co.uk/news/uk-northern-ireland-52494748|title=Coronavirus: Rise in deaths in NI care homes|date=1 May 2020|via=BBC News}}</ref>\n\nOn 2 May, a further 66 cases and 11 deaths were reported, bringing the totals to 3,689 cases and 376 deaths.\n\nOn 3 May, a further 78 cases and 5 deaths were reported, bringing the totals to 3,767 cases and 381 deaths.\n\nOn 4 May, a further 69 cases and 6 deaths were reported, bringing the totals to 3,836 cases and 387 deaths.\n\n==Field hospitals==\n\nIn mid-March HSC Northern Ireland started planning to open a [[NHS COVID-19 critical care hospitals|COVID-19 field hospital]] similar to those being introduced in [[England]]. The tower block of [[Belfast City Hospital]] was chosen as the first such facility, with 230 beds and staff from around the nation.<ref name=\"BBC52129644\">{{Cite news|url=https://www.bbc.co.uk/news/uk-northern-ireland-52129644|title=Coronavirus: City Hospital to host NI's first Nightingale|work=BBC News|accessdate=2 April 2020|language=en-GB}}</ref><ref name=\":7\">{{Cite web|url=https://www.health-ni.gov.uk/news/city-hospital-be-northern-irelands-first-nightingale-hospital|title=City hospital to be Northern Ireland\u2019s first Nightingale hospital|date=2 April 2020|website=Health|language=en|accessdate=6 April 2020}}</ref> The same report also stated that First Minister Arlene Foster had revealed that a Nightingale hospital could be based at the [[Eikon Exhibition Centre]] in [[Balmoral Park, Lisburn|Balmoral Park]], and that the Department of Health was assessing its potential as a second Nightingale facility in preparation for a possible second wave later in 2020.<ref name=\"BBC52129644\"/>\n\n==Statistics==\nThe official death toll from the Department of Health and Public Health Agency counts those who have died within 28 days of a Covid-19 diagnosis, whether or not it was the cause of their death. It mostly consists of hospital deaths, but also includes coronavirus-positive deaths in care homes and the community that are reported by the health service. The [[Northern Ireland Statistics and Research Agency]] (NISRA) gives a higher death toll, as is also counts \"suspected cases\" where Covid-19 was mentioned on the death certificate but no test was done.<ref>[https://www.bbc.co.uk/news/uk-northern-ireland-52291997 \"Coronavirus deaths: Why NI's statistics are changing\"]. BBC News, 15 April 2020.</ref>\n\n===Confirmed cases & deaths===\n\nCases are likely to be higher as statistics are based on positive test results. Suspected hospital discharges combined with suspected inpatients gives a higher total.\n\n====Confirmed cases====\n\n{{Graph:Chart\n|width=850\n|colors=#F46D43, #000000\n|showValues=offset:1\n|xAxisTitle=Date\n|xAxisAngle=-60\n|type=rect\n|x=29 Feb, 1 Mar, 2 Mar, 3 Mar, 4 Mar, 5 Mar, 6 Mar, 7 Mar, 8 Mar, 9 Mar, 10 Mar, 11 Mar, 12 Mar, 13 Mar, 14 Mar, 15 Mar, 16 Mar, 17 Mar, 18 Mar, 19 Mar, 20 Mar, 21 Mar, 22 Mar, 23 Mar, 24 Mar, 25 Mar, 26 Mar, 27 Mar, 28 Mar, 29 Mar, 30 Mar, 31 Mar, 1 Apr, 2 Apr, 3 Apr, 4 Apr, 5 Apr, 6 Apr, 7 Apr, 8 Apr, 9 Apr, 10 Apr, 11 Apr, 12 Apr, 13 Apr, 14 Apr, 15 Apr, 16 Apr, 17 Apr, 18 Apr, 19 Apr, 20 Apr, 22 Apr, 23 Apr, 24 Apr, 25 Apr, 26 Apr, 27 Apr, 28 Apr, 29 Apr, 30 Apr, 1 May, 2 May, 3 May, 4 May\n|yAxisTitle=No. of new cases\n|legend=Legend\n|y1=1, 0, 0, 0, 2, 0, 1, 3, 5, 0, 4, 2, 2, 9, 5, 11, 7, 10, 6, 9, 9, 22, 20, 20, 24, 37, 32, 34, 49, 86, 123, 53, 103, 85, 130, 94, 91, 69, 97, 84, 138, 112, 128, 89, 76, 85, 121, 113, 137, 148, 159, 83, 146, 142, 106, 104, 82, 66, 34, 55, 73, 87, 63, 78, 69\n|y1Title=New cases per day\n|yGrid= |xGrid=\n}}\n\n====Confirmed deaths====\n\n{{Graph:Chart\n|width=850\n|colors=#A50026\n|showValues=offset:1\n|xAxisTitle=Date\n|xAxisAngle=-60\n|type=rect\n|x=19 Mar, 20 Mar, 21 Mar, 22 Mar, 23 Mar, 24 Mar, 25 Mar, 26 Mar, 27 Mar, 28 Mar, 29 Mar, 30 Mar, 31 Mar, 1 Apr, 2 Apr, 3 Apr, 4 Apr, 5 Apr, 6 Apr, 7 Apr, 8 Apr, 9 Apr, 10 Apr, 11 Apr, 12 Apr, 13 Apr, 14 Apr, 15 Apr, 16 Apr, 17 Apr, 18 Apr, 19 Apr, 20 Apr, 21 Apr, 22 Apr, 23 Apr, 24 Apr, 25 Apr, 26 Apr, 27 Apr, 28 Apr, 29 Apr, 30 Apr, 1 May, 2 May, 3 May, 4 May\n|yAxisTitle=No. of deaths\n|legend=Legend\n|y=1, 0, 0, 1, 2, 1, 2, 3, 3, 2, 6, 1, 6, 2, 6, 12, 8, 7, 7, 3, 5, 4, 10, 15, 11, 6, 10, 6, 18, 18, 17, 1, 13, 9, 34, 13, 15, 16, 5, 10, 20, 9, 9, 18, 11, 5, 6\n|y1Title=Deaths per day\n|yGrid= |xGrid=\n}}\n\n====Total confirmed cases an